CNN's @rosaflorescnn reports.

node.text: Anger over a controversial tax hike has turned into weeks of protests against police violence in Colombia. More than 42 people have been killed and hundreds have been injured. CNN’s Stefano Pozzebon reports from Bogota, Colombia.

node.title: ‘They have nothing to lose’: Protesters storm streets of Colombia

node.text:
Florida A&M University students got a welcome surprise when the university announced it would be paying off student financial balances for the 2020-2021 school year. More than 20 historically Black colleges and universities have forgiven student debt using funds from the Coronavirus Aid, Relief and Economic Security Act. The schools have paid more than $25 million in student debt.⁠
⁠
(📸: Christian Whitaker/Florida A&M University)

node.text:
Jamaica’s Elaine Thompson-Herah became the first-ever woman to win the 100 meter and 200 meter sprint double at two consecutive Olympic Games. She won gold in the 200 meter in 21.53 seconds on Tuesday — the second fastest time in history.⁠
⁠
In men’s athletics, only Usain Bolt has surpassed this feat, winning the sprint double on three straight occasions – Beijing 2008, London 2012 and Rio 2016.⁠
⁠
(📸: Giuseppe Cacace/AFP/Getty Images)

node.text:
Norwegian Karsten Warholm won the men’s Olympic 400-meter hurdles, finishing in 45.94 seconds and shattering his own world record by more than half a second. “That was the best race in Olympic history,” said USA’s Rai Benjamin, who finished second in the race and won silver.⁠
⁠
(📸: Giuseppe Cacace/AFP/Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on August 03, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Diving champion Tom Daley said he was knitting a dog sweater during women's final MAA adidas GREAT BRITAIN A13-1-01 A13- CNN සපා'.

node.text:
If competitive diving doesn't work out, Tom Daley can always pursue a career as a knitwear designer. The Olympic gold medalist had his eyes on the wool and not the water, in a photo of him knitting in the stands at the women's three-meter springboard final in Tokyo on Sunday. The 27-year-old athlete took up knitting and crochet last March to get himself through the coronavirus lockdown, creating a profile on Instagram to share his creations with fans. "The one thing that has kept me sane throughout this whole process is my love for knitting and crochet and all things stitching," he wrote on Instagram.⁠
⁠
(📸: Clive Rose/Getty Images)

node.text:
New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo sexually harassed multiple women, according to the state attorney general report. The investigation found that Cuomo engaged in “unwelcome and nonconsensual touching,” made comments of a “suggestive” sexual nature and created a “hostile work environment for women.” Cuomo’s behavior was not limited to members of his own staff, but extended to other state employees, including a State Trooper on his protective detail, as well as members of the public, the attorney general’s report said.⁠
⁠
(📸: Spencer Platt/AFP/Getty Images)⁠

node.text:
China's Guan Chenchen won gold in the women's balance beam final at the Tokyo Olympics  Tuesday as US gymnastics star Simone Biles overcame mental health challenges to claim a bronze. Biles finished her routine with a standing ovation from the crowd. She displayed a confident return to form after previously having withdrawn from other events due to mental health concerns. Tap the link in our bio to learn more.⁠
⁠
(📸: Laurence Griffiths/Getty Images)⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on August 03, 2021. May be an image of ‎1 person and ‎text that says '‎Laurel Hubbard becomes first openly transgender woman to compete at an Olympics لا COBRA‎'‎‎.

node.text:
New Zealand weightlifter Laurel Hubbard became the first-ever openly transgender woman to compete in the 125-year history of the modern Olympics when she took part in the women’s super-heavyweight +87kg category on Monday in Japan. Hubbard failed in all three of her attempts in the snatch, ending her bid for a medal. She was up against nine other athletes in the competition, with China’s world record holder, Li Wenwen, the favorite to win gold. Hubbard competed in men’s weightlifting competitions before coming out in 2013. Tap the link in our bio to learn more.⁠
⁠
(📸: Wally Skalij /Los Angeles Times via Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on August 02, 2021. May be an image of 3 people, child and text that says 'Michigan father rushed into burning home to save his twin 18-month-old daughters'.

node.text:
Earlier this month, Ray Lucas and his girlfriend Shi'Ann Brown returned after a trip to the corner store to find their Michigan home engulfed in flames — and their twin daughters were trapped inside. Lucas' mother, who had been watching the 18-month-old girls, was panicking in the front yard in Eastpointe, Michigan. "I was speechless. Action took over me. I ran into the house to get my babies," Lucas, 23, told CNN. Lucas suffered from burns on his arms, ears, face and neck, and was blind for three days because his corneas were damaged and swelled up due to smoke exposure. Tap the link in our bio to learn more. ⁠
⁠
(📸: Courtesy Ray Lucas)

May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Dolly Parton invested Whitney Houston cover royalties in Black Nashville neighborhood n 1973 Parton wrote the ballad," Will Always Love You" which became a worldwide hit when Houston covered it in 1992 Billy CNN'.

node.text:
Dolly Parton revealed that she invested her royalties from Whitney Houston's cover of "I Will Always Love You" into a Black community in Nashville. The Grammy Award-winning singer, songwriter, producer and actress wrote and performed the song in 1973 as a farewell to her then business partner, Porter Wagoner. However, it wasn't until Houston covered it for the 1992 romantic drama "The Bodyguard" that it became a worldwide hit. The ballad — which spent 14 weeks at the top of the US Billboard Hot 100 — earned Parton $10 million in royalties in the 1990s, according to Forbes. "I bought my big office complex down in Nashville," the 75-year-old country icon explained. "I thought this is a wonderful place to be."⁠
⁠
(📸: Nathan Congleton/NBC/NBCU Photo Bank via Getty Images)

node.text:
Follow ➡️ @cnnclimate ➡️ Residents of Nigeria are used to the yearly floods that engulf Lagos, a low-lying city on Nigeria's Atlantic coast, during the months of March to November. In mid-July, however, the major business district of Lagos Island experienced one of its worst floods in recent years. Home to more than 24 million people, Africa's most populous city may become uninhabitable by the end of this century as sea levels rise due to climate change, scientific projections suggest.
